Why are Relationships Used?
Reduce data redundancy (duplicate data)
Maintain data integrity
Connect related tables
Make data retrieval easier using JOINs
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Types of Relationships in MySQL

There are four main types:
One-to-One (1:1)
One-to-Many (1:N)
Many-to-One (N:1)
Many-to-Many (M:N)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. One-to-One (1:1)

One record in Table A is related to only one record in Table B.
Person
+-----------+
| person_id |
| name      |
+-----------+
      |
      | 1 : 1
      |
Passport
+--------------+
| passport_id  |
| person_id FK |
| passport_no  |
+--------------+

CREATE TABLE Person (
    person_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(50)
);

INSERT INTO Person VALUES (1, 'Aniket');
INSERT INTO Person VALUES (2, 'Rahul');
INSERT INTO Person VALUES (3, 'Priya');
INSERT INTO Person VALUES (4, 'Amit');
INSERT INTO Person VALUES (5, 'Sneha');

CREATE TABLE Passport (
    passport_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    passport_no VARCHAR(20),
    person_id INT UNIQUE,
    FOREIGN KEY (person_id) REFERENCES Person(person_id)
);

INSERT INTO Passport VALUES (101, 'P1234567', 1);
INSERT INTO Passport VALUES (102, 'P2345678', 2);
INSERT INTO Passport VALUES (103, 'P3456789', 3);
INSERT INTO Passport VALUES (104, 'P4567890', 4);
INSERT INTO Passport VALUES (105, 'P5678901', 5);

SELECT * FROM Person;
SELECT * FROM Passport;

